*Thought for a couple of seconds

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*My opinion is very positive. The PZoom boxes may become one of the signature f
eatures of ProofZoom.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*They solve a real expository problem: a proof often has a main line of thought
, but also contains local "pain points" where a reader may need three or four e
xtra steps. If we put every such step into the main proof, the proof becomes lo
ng and heavy. If we omit them, the proof is no longer truly ProofZoom. The expa
ndable box gives the best of both worlds.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*The main proof remains elegant:

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*Here is the idea.

*Here is the key construction.

*Here is the decisive contradiction.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*But the reader who hesitates can click:

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*PZoom: why does this follow?

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*and get the missing micro-proof.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*This is especially valuable for gifted high-school students, undergraduates, a
nd mathematicians reading outside their specialty. They often do not need every
 detail, but when they do need one, they need it exactly at that point.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*I would treat these boxes as a ProofZoom convention, but use them sparingly. T
oo many boxes will make the page look fragmented. The best use is for moments l
ike:

*
[13]
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*PZoom: prove that ?(a) escapes the image of ^^ed
Missing character: There is no ^^ed in font cmr10!

*PZoom: why this union is well-ordered

*PZoom: why this set is transitive

*PZoom: why the least counterexample argument works

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*In other words, use them for genuine proof bottlenecks, not routine algebra or
 definitions.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*The name PZoom is also good. It is short, distinctive, and tied to the platfor
m. It says: "Here is where we zoom in."

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*My second question:

*Although the PZoom box is a simple pedagogical device, it took approx. one yea
r for this to occur to me despite the fact that I had  used these boxes in my c
lass notes where the contents of the boxes were visible on first reading becaus
e it was in the printed notes.  Now the question is, would mathematicians criti
cize the PZoom boxes because  a good fraction of the reader population would cl
ick on the boxes without trying to derive the subproofs themselves?

*Thought for a couple of seconds

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*Some mathematicians may make that criticism, but I do not think it is a seriou
s objection. In fact, the objection misunderstands the purpose of ProofZoom.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*A proof exposition is not an exam. Its first duty is not to test the reader, b
ut to make the mathematical structure visible.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*The PZoom box does not prevent the reader from thinking. It gives the reader a
 choice:

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*Try it yourself first, or open the zoomed proof when needed.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*That is pedagogically sound. A determined reader can pause before clicking. A 
stuck reader can click. A reader who already sees the step can skip it. This is
 much better than a printed proof, where the sub-proof is either always visible
 and interrupts the flow, or absent and leaves a gap.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*I would compare it to hints and solutions in a good problem book. The mere exi
stence of a hint does not weaken the book. It improves the book, provided the h
int is well placed and not overused.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*The criticism to avoid is not "readers may click too soon." The real danger is
 overuse. If every second line has a PZoom box, the reader may stop following t
he main proof and simply hop from expansion to expansion. But if the boxes are 
reserved for genuine bottlenecks, then they become a strength.

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*You can also reduce the criticism by using labels that invite effort. For exam
ple:

*
(Please type a command or say `\end')
*PZoom: Try first - why does \(\psi(a)\notin\operatorname{im}(\phi)\)?
